Preliminaries

In this help sheet, we will test for and estimate a cointegrating relationship between Stimsons public policy mood, Mood, (higher values mean the public has a preference for more liberal social policies) and the economic portion of economic expectations, filtbf (predicted economic expectations based on inflation, unemployment and the coincident economic indicator index) and the generosity of public policy, PolAvg (based on average federal social spending, higher values are more generous).

Durr (1993) contends that Americans preference for a more or less activist federal government (Mood) is tied to expectations about the future of the economy (filtbf). When the public expects the future of the economy to be strong, producing jobs and tax revenues, it is willing to pay for the broadening of the social safety net for everyone. In contrast, visions of a gloomy economic future limit the desire for government spending to combat social ills. In addition, public preferences exhibit a thermostatic relationship with policy outcomes (PolAvg): the more liberal (expansive) policy is, the less of it the public will demand. Durr found each of these three time series to be unit root processes without drift or trend. His theoretical argument thus leads us to expect that while each is individually a unit root process, the stochastic trends in these variables are shared.

Ferguson, Kellstedt, and Linn (2015) extended Durrs analysis and in what follows we will test Durrs conjecture with the updated data.

Conduct Unit Root Tests

Use the DF test to determine whether public policy mood (Mood), filetered business expectations (filtbf), and average liberalism of policy outcomes (PolAvg) are unit root processes.

Conclusions

We cannot reject the null hypothesis that each of these series are unit root processes, although its not clear if Mood is or is not a unit root process. We will consider this uncertainty later.

Assuming Mood is a unit root, we can test for cointegration. First, we will cover the Engle-Granger two-step approach and then the single-equation GECM approach.

Engle-Granger Step 1

Estimate a Cointegrating Regression

Based on Durrs argument, we specify a cointegrating regression. Specifically, In Durrs theory, the continual presence of societal problems and the publics awareness that governments ability to spend depends on tax revenues will prevent public policy mood from straying too far from economic expectations and policy outcomes so that any shocks to public policy mood will be temporary such that:

\[ Mood_t = D_{lr} + \lambda_1 filtbf_t + \lambda_2 PolAvg_t + \mu_t \]

where \(\mu_t\) must be stationary. If the error is \(I(1)\), then public policy preferences would cumulate and deviations of Mood from filtbf and PolAvg would not be eliminated over time.

Before we estimate the cointegrating regression, we need to decide the appropriate form of deterministics in the model, \(D_{lr}\). We want to include deterministics that affect the long-run relationship, i.e., how Mood evolves over time in relationship with filtbf and PolAvg.

  • We dont anticipate that in equilibrium the values of Mood, filtbf, and PolAvg are the same, thus we want to include a constant, \(\lambda_0\), to allow there to be a mean difference between the series in equilibrium.

  • A trend makes little sense (no series is drifting/trending), so we will not include it in the test regression.

\[ Mood_t = \lambda_0 + \lambda_1 filtbf_t + \lambda_2 PolAvg_t + \mu_t \]

Estimate the cointegrating regression:

mystatica <- dynlm(Mood ~ PolAvg +  filtbf, data=data.ts2)
summary(mystatica)

Test Residuals for Cointegration

Having estimated the cointegrating regression, our next task is to determine whether the residuals are stationary. If they are, then Mood is cointegrated with at least one of the two \(I(1)\) regressors (filtbf and/or PolAvg). Thus, we test for cointegration using a unit root test applied to the residuals from the cointegrating regression. We will use a Dickey-Fuller test, but we could use other unit root tests as well.

Remember that we do not include a constant or trend in the DF test regression because the residuals have a mean of zero and there is no trend. I choose \(pmax=12\) for the test and test for serial correlation up through 12 lags. Note The test statistic in this output does not follow the Dickey-Fuller distribution, so we cannot use the p-values from the adf.tests() function. The test statistic is still the \(t\)-value on lagged \(\hat{\mu}\). We are just using the Dickey Fuller test to select the number of lags, \(p\), for the test regression and then get the test statistic from that regression.

adf.tests(mystatica$residuals, pmax = 12, lmtestorder = 12, type = "none")

Critical values of Dickey Fuller Test

The appropriate critical values to be used to test the null hypothesis that the residuals contain a unit root and therefore that the variables are not cointegrated can be calculated from the tables found here: https://www.econstor.eu/bitstream/10419/67744/1/616664753.pdf. We need 3 pieces of information:

  1. Which test statistic, i.e., which table of critical values? Because the static regression included a constant, we will use Table 2 and consider \(\tau_c\).
  2. \(n\). For the residual-based test we use the case where \(N\) is the number of \(I(1)\) variables for which the null of no cointegration is being tested (3).
  3. \(T\). \(T\) is the sample size used for the cointegrating regression which is 159.

We will use the 0.05 critical value.

To compute the critical value we use the formula: \(\beta_{\infty} + \beta_/T + \beta_/T^2 + \beta_/T^3\), where \(\beta_{\infty}\) is the asymptotic critical value given the form of the test regression and the remaining \(\beta_i\) are used to correct based on sample size. \(T\)

  1. Find the appropriate table based on whether there is a constant or constant and trend in the test regression (Here just constant, table 2).
  2. Find row for N=3. We will use alpha level of .05. Note the various \(\beta\) values. -3.74066 , -8.5631, -10.852, 27.982.
  3. Sample size \(T\): \(T=159\).
  4. Calculate the following formula for the approximate critical value: \(q(T_i) = \beta_{\infty} + \beta_1(T_i)^{-1} + \beta_2(T_i)^{-2} - \beta_3(T_i)^{-3}\).

\[ -3.74066- 8.5631/159-10.852/(159^2) + 27.982/(159^3) = -3.74938. \]

The test statistic value is -2.383. Thus, we fail to reject the null of no cointegration, i.e., we fail to reject the null that the residuals follow a unit root process at the 0.05 level of significance and thus conclude the series are not cointegrated. If this was the end result of our analysis, wed want to estimate the relationship between these series in first-differences as there is no stable long-run relationship between the series. However, previous work suggests mood was impacted by the Vietnam war (Mood shifted liberal), the Iraq war (Mood shifted liberal), and the Iranian Hostage crisis (Mood shifted conservative), so we will allow the mean of mood in equilibrium to vary with each intervention.

Estimate the Cointegrating Regression with Interventions

The values used for the intervention variables are given below.

  • Values of Vietnam: 0, 0.03, 0.06, 0.09, 0.15, 0.24, 0.39, 0.64, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1 (through 1975), 0, 0, 0 after. The idea here is that Vietnam became more relevant over time as more and more Americans were killed and shifted the mean of any long-run relationship.

  • Values of Iraq: 0 before first quarter 2003 and 1 after. The Iraq war was not over by the end of the sample, so this allows the mean of any long-run relationship to change during the war.

  • Values of IranHost: 0 before fourth quarter 1979, then 1 for 6 quarters and then 0.64, 0.39, 0.24, 0.15, 0.09, 0.06, 0.03, then 0 after.

Lets estimate the cointegrating regression with these intervention variables:

mystatic <- dynlm(Mood ~ PolAvg +  filtbf + IranHost + Vietnam + Iraq, data = data.ts2)

Critical values of Dickey Fuller Test with Interventions

We cannot use the MacKinnon tables to calculate the appropriate critical value, as the tables do not allow for interventions. Instead, we need to simiulate them. We do so by following these steps:

  1. Simulate \(n-1\) unit root processes of length \(T\), without a constant. Here we need to simulate two random walks without drift.
  2. Generate the first differences of the intervention variables in \(D_{lr}\) used in the test regression. (If none, we have the MacKinnon case.)
  3. Simulate \(y_t\) as an \(I(1)\) variable without a constant and as a function of the first differences of the intervention variables in \(D_{lr}\) but not \(\mathbf{X_t}\). (We always generate critical values under the null hypothesis, so that the series are unrelated in the long-run.) This creates a permanent change in \(y_t\) with each increment of the differenced intervention. Put differently, we use first difference interventions because y is a unit root and thus permanently incorporates the shocks. Again, if there are no interventions, we have the MacKinnon case.)
  4. Regress \(y_t\)on \(D_{lr}\) (not the first differences of interventions) and \(\mathbf{X_t}\) and save the residuals. We estimate the cointegrating regression with the original interventions, which causes mean shifts in any cointegrating relationship. (If no interventions, simulate \(y_t\) omitting the interventions. Again, the MacKinnon case.)
  5. Conduct a unit root test on the residuals and save the test statistic.
  6. Repeat a large number of times, say 50,000.
  7. Calculate the desired percentile from the resulting distribution of the test statistic. This is the critical value for the test.
  8. Compare the critical value with the sample statistic in your cointegrating regression and draw an inference.

Note if the individual series in our analysis contained drift, we would simulate the variables with a constant and then add a trend to the cointegrating regression.

First, Im going to create functions to use in the simulations.

  • tslag: to lag a variable and add NA to the first observation, so the number of observations stays constant.

  • tsdiff: to first difference a variable and add NA to the first observation so that the number of observations is unchanged.

  • gen.unit.root: to generate a unit root without drift or trend

  • gen.y: to generate a unit root without drift or trend with three intervention variables

set.seed(19852015)
tslag<-function(y,d=1){
  n<-length(y)
  c(rep(NA,d),y)[1:n]
}

tsdiff <- function(y, d = 1){
  n <- length(y)
 
  c(rep(NA,d),diff(y))[1:n]
 
}

gen.unit.root <- function(n){
 
  e.x <- rnorm(n)
  x <- double(n)
  x[1] <- rnorm(1)
  for(i in 2:n){
    x[i] <- x[i-1] + e.x[i]
  }
  x
}
gen.y <- function(n, var1, var2, var3){
  #set.seed(19852015)
  e.y <- rnorm(n)
  y <- double(n)
  y[1] <- rnorm(1)
  for(i in 2:n){
    y[i] <- y[i-1] +var1[i] + var2[i] + var3[i] +  e.y[i]
  }
  y
}

Generate MacKinnon Critical Value for the Dickey Fuller Test with a Constant

Lets first replicate the case with no interventions and compare to the appropriate MacKinnon table. To approximate the asymptotic critical values for the DF test, I generate time series with 15000 observations. Here Im only going to use 10,000 replications as this takes a long time to run.

dfuller.valuesM <- function(nsim,T){
    pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0,      # Minimum value of the progress bar
                     max = nsim, # Maximum value of the progress bar
                     style = 3,    # Progress bar style (also available style = 1 and style = 2)
                     width = 50,   # Progress bar width. Defaults to getOption("width")
                     char = "=")   # Character used to create the bar

  out <- vector(mode="list", length=nsim)
  for(m in 1:nsim){
x1 <-  gen.unit.root(n=T)  # Generate x1 as a unit root
x2 <-  gen.unit.root(n=T)  # Generate x2 as a unit root
y <- gen.unit.root(n=T)    # Generate y as a unit root
lm.df <- summary(lm(y~ x1 + x2)) #Estimate the cointegrating regression with a constant
muhat <- lm.df$residuals         #Harvest the residuals
mu.diff <- tsdiff(muhat)   #First difference the residual for dependent variable in DF test
    lag.mu <- tslag(muhat)          #Lag the residuals for DF test
    lm.df <- summary(lm(mu.diff~lag.mu -1))  #Estimate test regression without a constant
    t.df <- lm.df$coefficients[,3][[1]]      #Harvest the t-statistic from the results
    out[[m]] <- t.df                         #Add the t-statistic to out
 # setTxtProgressBar(pb, m)
  }
  unlist(out)
}

Dynamic OLS

If you reject the null of no cointegration, you need to ask which variables are part of the cointegrating relationship? You can use DOLS to answer this question. DOLS adds leads and lags of the regressors in first differences to the static cointegrating regression.

\[ y_t = D_{lr} + \lambda_{1} x_{1t} + \lambda_{2} x_{2t} + ...+\lambda_{n} x_{nt} + \sum_{j=1}^n \sum_{s=1}^r \eta_{js} \Delta x_{jt\pm s} +\mu_t \]

where \(r\) is large enough to ensure the regressors are not correlated with the error. Including the additional lag and lead terms soaks up the long-run correlation between the regressors and the errors. As a result, the bias in the estimates of the long-run relationship tend to be smaller in DOLS than in the static cointegrating regression. Moreover, we can test restrictions on the cointegrating vector using Newey-West heteroscedastic and autocorrelation consistent standard errors.

Ive estimated this equation setting \(r=2\) and \(r=4\).

myDOLS<- dynlm(Mood~  PolAvg +  L(d(PolAvg),c(-1, -2, 1, 2)) + filtbf + L(d(filtbf),c(-1, -2, 1, 2)) +  IranHost + Vietnam + Iraq, data=data.ts2)

myDOLSHAC <- coeftest(myDOLS, vcov = vcovHAC(myDOLS))

Engle-Granger Step 2

Cointegration implies that the any disequilibrium should drive Mood to change to restore the long-run cointegrating relationship/equilibrium. Thus, in step two we estimate an error correction model in which changes in Mood are a function of the long-run disequilibrium in the previous period, \(\hat{\mu}_t\) and contemporaneous changes in the independent variables. The form of this regression is an ECM.

Before we estimate the ECM, we need to determine \(D_{sr}\). We want to allow for the events to have a temporary effect on \(\Delta y_t\), so we enter the first-differenced interventions in step two.

Well also test for serial correlation in the residuals, but it is important to note that this regression should meet all the TS regression assumptions.

second.step <- dynlm(d(Mood)~ L(DOLS.DISEQ)  + d(Vietnam) + d(IranHost) + d(Iraq) +  d(PolAvg) + d(filtbf)+  L(d(PolAvg),1) + L(d(filtbf),1) + L(d(Mood),1) + L(d(Mood),4)+ L(d(Mood),8), data=data.ts2)

GECM t-test

To conduct the ECM \(t\)-test for cointegration, we estimate the generalized error correction model:

\[\Delta y_t = D_t -\alpha_1^* y_{t-1}-\beta_1^* x_{1t-1} - \beta_2^* x_{2t-1} - - \beta_n^* x_{nt-1} + \psi_{1}\Delta x_{1t} + \psi_{2}\Delta x_{2t} + , \psi_{j}\Delta x_{jt}+ \varepsilon_t \]

where we also include enough lagged changes in the variables to ensure the residuals are white noise. The GECM should also include the interventions in the static ciontegrating regression plus first differences of those interventions. I experimented a bit with different lag lengths of \(\Delta y_t\) and found lag 1, lag 4, and lag 8 just did the trick.

\[\Delta Mood_t = D_t -\alpha_1^* Mood_{t-1}-\beta_1^* PolAvg_{1t-1} + \beta_2^*Vietnam_t + \beta_3*Hostages_t + \beta_4^*Iraq_t + \\ \psi_{1}\Delta PolAvg_{t} + \psi_{2}\Delta Vietnam_t + \psi_{3}\Delta Hostages_t +\psi_{4}\Delta Iraq_t + \\ \psi_{4}\Delta filtbf_{t}+ \psi_{5}\Delta filtbf_{t-1}+ \psi_{6}\Delta Mood_{t-1} + \psi_{7}\Delta Mood_{t-4}+ \psi_{8}\Delta Mood_{t-8} +\varepsilon_t \]

GECM <- dynlm(d(Mood)~ L(Mood)+ L(PolAvg)+
                Vietnam + Iraq + IranHost+ 
                d(Vietnam) + d(Iraq) + d(IranHost) + 
                d(PolAvg) + L(d(PolAvg), 1) + d(filtbf) +  L(d(filtbf),1) +
                L(d(Mood),1) + L(d(Mood),4) + L(d(Mood),8)
              ,  data=data.ts2)


GECMHAC <- coeftest(GECM, vcov = vcovHAC(GECM))# Heteroscedastic and

Critical Values for the GECM \(t\)-test

Our interest in this test regression is on the t-statistic on lagged Mood, \(\alpha_1^*\). But is has a non-standard limiting distribution. If our GECM did not contain the levels intervention variables, we could use MacKinnons 2002 tables. This paper is in Canvas. For practice, we will calculate them here, but also simulate them to account for the interventions. Our GECM does not contain a trend but does contain a constant, so we will use table 3. We select the row for k=2 (two \(I(1)\) variables in our regression). We will use the 0.05 critical value

  1. Find appropriate table based on whether there is a constant and trend (here just constant, table 3).
  2. Find row for k equal to number of \(I(1)\) independent variables. We have 2 will use alpha level of .05. Note the various \(\theta\) values: -4.7970, -4.7970, -9.04, -5.6, -66.
  3. Compute adjusted sample size \(T_a\): \(T -(2*k-1) -d\): 168-(2*2-1)-4=161.
  4. Calculate following formula for approximate critical value: \(q(T_i) = \theta_{\infty} + \theta_1(T_i)^{-1} + \theta_2(T_i)^{-2} - \theta_3(T_i)^{-3}\).

\[ -3.2145 -3.21/161 -2.0/(161^2) -65/(161^3) = -3.234531 \]

The \(t\)-statistic on \(\hat{\alpha_1^*}\) in the GECM (the coefficient on lagged Mood) is -5.131, which is further from zero than the critical value. We could reject the null of no cointegration if there were not interventions. To see whether our conclusion is the same with interventions we again need to simulate the limiting distribution.

We generate the data in the same manner as above, but now estimate the GECM and harvest the \(t\)-statistic on lagged Mood. First we will estimate the MacKinnon case with no interventions and compare with the asymptotic value from MacKinnon: -3.2145.

gecmt.values <- function(nsim, T){
    pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0,      # Minimum value of the progress bar
                     max = nsim, # Maximum value of the progress bar
                     style = 3,    # Progress bar style (also available style = 1 and style = 2)
                     width = 50,   # Progress bar width. Defaults to getOption("width")
                     char = "=")   # Character used to create the bar

  out <- vector(mode="list", length=nsim)
  for(m in 1:nsim){
  x1 <- gen.unit.root(n=T)
  y <- gen.unit.root(n=T)
  y.diff <- tsdiff(y)
  x1.diff <- tsdiff(x1)
   y.lag <- tslag(y)
  x1.lag <- tslag(x1)
lm.df <- summary(lm(y.diff~ y.lag + x1.lag + x1.diff ))
    t.df <- lm.df$coefficients[,3][[2]]
    out[[m]] <- t.df
    #setTxtProgressBar(pb, m)
  }
  unlist(out)
}

gecmt.valuesMood <- function(nsim, T){
    pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0,      # Minimum value of the progress bar

  for(m in 1:nsim){
  x1 <- gen.unit.root(n=T)

  Hostages <- data$IranHost[1:T]
  Iraq <- data$Iraq[1:T]

  t.df <- lm.df$coefficients[,3][[2]]
  out[[m]] <- t.df
    #setTxtProgressBar(pb, m)
  }
  unlist(out)
}

We can draw inferences directly from this model. Here, like in the Engle-Granger Two-Step approach, because weve determined the variables are cointegrated, each righthand-side variable is stationary and we can use standard critical values for all hypothesis tests. Specifically, we can normalize the long-run relationship with respect to any element of \(\mathbf{X_{t-1}}\), as well as \(y_{t-1}\), to show that each \(\beta_{j1}\) is a coefficient on a mean-zero stationary variable and thus that standard limiting distributions apply.

Interpretation

We can ask the same questions of either model that we did in the stationary case:

  • What is the Direct Effect of a Unit Change in \(x_t\) (PolAvg) on \(y_t\) (Mood)?

  • What is the Total Effect (LRM) of a Unit Change in \(x_{t}\) (PolAvg) on \(y_{t}\) (Mood)?

  • What is the Long-Run Equilibrium?

  • How Quickly Does \(y_{t}\) (Mood) Change to Restore Equilibrium Following a Change in \(x_{t}\) (PolAvg)

  • How do the effects play out over time?

    • How Long Before Most of the Effect Plays Out?

    • How Long Before the Effect has Effectively Dissipated?

Lets answer these questions and compare the results from the two-step ECM and the GECM.

First, lets look at the results from both approaches.

Direct Effects

The direct effects of the regressors is given by the coefficients on changes in both the ECM and GECM in columns 2 and 3. Although the two methods are asymptotically equivalent, the coefficients in finite samples will differ, sometimes by quite a bit.

  • The contemporaneous direct effect of PolAvg is given by -0.084 in the ECM and -0.125 in the GECM. The immediate change in Mood with a one-unit increase in in the generosity of policy leads to a drop of 0.084 or 0.125 in Mood in the same period.

  • The direct effect of filtbf is given by 0.042 in the ECM and 0.044 in the GECM. A one-unit increase in economic expectations leads to a positive change in Mood of about .04 in either model.

  • The direct effect of involvement in Vietnam is quite different in the two models. It is not distinguishable from zero in the ECM but negative and significant in the GECM. When Vietnam began, Mood became more conservative.

Long-run Multipliers

Two Step: Coefficients on levels of \(I(1)\) regressors in CI regression:\[ y_t = \hat{D}_{lr} +\hat{\lambda}_{1} x_{1t} + \hat{\lambda}_{2} x_{2t} + ...+ \hat{\lambda}_{j} x_{jt} \]

In our example \(\hat{\lambda}\):\[ Mood_t = \hat{\lambda_0} + \hat{\lambda}_{V} Vietnam_t + \hat{\lambda}_H Hostages_t + \hat{\lambda}_I Iraq_t +\hat{\lambda}_{1} PolAvg_{1t} \]

Or:

\[ Mood_t = 72.38+ 9.52 Vietnam_t - 4.26 Hostages_t + 5.34 Iraq_t - 0.31 PolAvg_{1t} \]

The long-run multiplier for PolAvg is -0.31. Every point increase in the generosity of public policy leads to a decrease in the preference for my liberal policies of 0.31.

The long-run multiplier for Vietnam is 9.52, for Hostages is -4.26, and for Iraq is 5.34.

GECM:

\[ -\frac{\hat{\beta}_{j}^*}{\hat{\alpha}_1^*}x_{jt-1} \]

\[ \Delta Mood_t = 22.80 -0.298Mood_{t-1}-0.117 PolAvg_{t-1} - 1.614 Hostages_t + 2.72 Vietnam_t + 1.37 Iraq_t \\- 2.02\Delta Vietnam_{t} + 0.91 \Delta Hostages_t + 4.54\Delta Iraq_t - 0.13\Delta PolAvg_{t} + 0.04 \Delta filtbf_t \\-0.11 \Delta PolAvg_{t-1} - 0.04 \Delta filtbf_{t-1} -0.05 \Delta Mood_{t-1} + 0.15 \Delta Mood_{t-4} + 0.09 \Delta Mood_{t-8} \]

For PolAvg: \(-(-0.117/-0.298)=-0.393\)

For Vietnam: \(-(2.72/-0.298)=9.128\)

For Hostages: \(-(1.614/-0.298)=5.416\)

For Iraq: $-(1.37/-0.298)=4.597$

The LRM differ slightly in sample.

Long-run Equilibrium

Whereas in the stationary case, the equilibrium is a fixed point, in the cointegrated case, the equilibrium is moving over time:

Two Step: CI regression from step 1:

\[ y_t = \hat{D}_{lr} + \hat{\lambda}_{1} x_{1t} + \hat{\lambda}_{2} x_{2t} + ... + \hat{\lambda}_{j} x_{jt} \]

In our example:

\[ Mood_t = \hat{\lambda_0} + \hat{\lambda}_{V} Vietnam + \hat{\lambda}_H Hostages + \hat{\lambda} Iraq +\hat{\lambda}_{1} PolAvg_{t} \]

or:

\[ Mood_t = 72.38+ 9.52 Vietnam_t - 4.26 Hostages_t + 5.34 Iraq_t - 0.31 PolAvg_{t} \]

GECM:

\[ y_t = \frac{\hat{\alpha}_0^*}{-\hat{\alpha}_1^*} + \frac{\hat{\delta}}{-\hat{\alpha}_1^*} t+ \frac{\sum_{j=1}^{n} \hat{\beta}_{j1}^* x_{jt}}{-\hat{\alpha}_1^*} \]

Or:

\[ Mood_t = \frac{22.80}{0.298} + \frac{2.72}{0.298}Vietnam_{t} -\frac{1.614}{0.298}Hostages + \frac{1.37}{0.298}Iraq_t + \frac{0.117}{0.298}PolAvg_{t} \]

Lets calculate the moving equilibrium from both approaches.

#Long-run relationship from GECM
LRRGECM <- GECM$coefficients[1]/(-GECM$coefficients[2]) + 
  GECM$coefficients[3]*model.frame(GECM)$"L(PolAvg)"/(-GECM$coefficients[2]) +
  GECM$coefficients[4]*model.frame(GECM)$Vietnam/(-GECM$coefficients[2])+ 
  GECM$coefficients[5]*model.frame(GECM)$Iraq/(-GECM$coefficients[2])+ 
  GECM$coefficients[6]*model.frame(GECM)$IranHost/(-GECM$coefficients[2])
LRRGECM.ts <- ts(LRRGECM, start = c(1971,1), end = c(2010,3), frequency = 4)

#Long-run relationship from First step of Two-Step Approach
LRRStatic.ts <- ts(mystatic2$fitted.values, start = c(1968,4), end = c(2010,3), frequency = 4)

#Combine the two over shared time period
LRE <- ts.union(LRRGECM.ts, LRRStatic.ts)
LRE <- na.omit(LRE)
#Put the two equilibria in a data frame and graph

  geom_line()

##              LRRGECM.ts LRRStatic.ts
## LRRGECM.ts    1.0000000    0.9729252
## LRRStatic.ts  0.9729252    1.0000000

The equilibria are highly correlated. Where they differ is in the onset of the interventions. This happens because the effects of the interventions in the GECM are conditional on the short-run dynamics, whereas they are not in the cointegrating regression. The dynamics in the GECM are going to be estimated better.

How Quickly Does \(y_{t}\) Change to Restore Equilibrium Following a Change in \(x_{t}\)

Two Step: The error correction rate is given by the coefficient on lagged residuals from CI regression, \(\hat{\gamma}\):

\[ \Delta y_t=\hat{D}_{sr} +\hat{\gamma} (\hat{\mu}_{t-1})+ \hat{\psi}_{1}\Delta x_{1t} + \hat{\psi}_{2}\Delta x_{2t} + +\hat{\psi}_{j}\Delta x_{jt} \]

In our example:

\[ \Delta Mood_t= -0.08 -0.294 (\hat{\mu}_{t-1})+ 0.412\Delta Vietnam_t - 0.37 \Delta Hostages_t + 6.98 \Delta Iraq_t - 0.09\Delta PolAvg_t \\+ 0.04\Delta filtbf_t - 0.04 \Delta Mood_{t-1} + 0.16 \Delta Mood_{t-4} + 0.10 \Delta Mood_{t-8} \]

\(\hat{\gamma}=-0.294\).

GECM: The error correction rate is given by the coefficient on lagged \(y_{t-1}\), \(\hat{\alpha}_1^*\).

\[ \Delta y_t = \hat{D}_t -\hat{\alpha_1}^* y_{t-1}-\hat{\beta}_1^* x_{1t-1} - \hat{\beta}_2^* x_{2t-1} - - \hat{\beta}_n^* x_{nt-1} + \hat{\psi}_{1}\Delta x_{1t} + \hat{\psi}_{2}\Delta x_{2t} + , \hat{\psi}_{j}\Delta x_{jt} \]

In our example:

\[ \Delta Mood_t = 22.80 -0.298Mood_{t-1}-0.117 PolAvg_{t-1} - 1.614 Hostages_t + 2.72 Vietnam_t + 1.37 Iraq_t - \\ 2.02\Delta Vietnam_{t}+ 0.91 \Delta Hostages_t + 4.54\Delta Iraq_t - 0.13\Delta PolAvg_{t} + 0.04 \Delta filtbf_t\\ -0.11 \Delta PolAvg_{t-1} - 0.04 \Delta filtbf_{t-1} -0.05 \Delta Mood_{t-1} + 0.15 \Delta Mood_{t-4} + 0.09 \Delta Mood_{t-8} \]

\(\hat{\alpha}_1^*=-0.298\).

In either model, about 29% of the disequilibrium is corrected in each period.

Impulse Response Functions

We want to know how \(y_t\) adjusts to return to equilibrium after a one-unit step increase in \(x_t\). Say, PolAvg increase permanently by one unit: Assume a one time change in PolAvg, such that \(\Delta PolAvg_t=1\) at time \(t\) and that \(Mood_{t-1}=0\).

Then calculate the path of Mood in each successive period. This can be tricky, especially (as here) when there are long lags of \(\Delta y_t\) in the model.

PolAvg.cirf <- data.frame(period = c(0:20),
                           PolAvgcIRF = NA_real_)

#GECM$coefficients[2] = Lag Mood = -0.3031263
#GECM$coefficients[3] = Lag PolAvg = -0.1165336  * 1 every period after zero
#GECM$coefficients[10] = Delta PolAvg = -0.07515562  * 1 only at zero period
#GECM$coefficients[11] = Lag Delta PolAvg = -0.1455531 * 1 only at first period
#GECM$coefficients[14] = Lag Delta Mood = -0.05470087
#GECM$coefficients[15] = Lag 4 Delta Mood =  0.1617978
#GECM$coefficients[16] =  Lag 8 Delta Mood = 0.06149369 

#Zero period
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[1] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*0 + GECM$coefficients[3]*0 + GECM$coefficients[10]*1 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 + GECM$coefficients[14]*0 + GECM$coefficients[15]*0 + GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

#First period after shock
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[2] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[1] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*1 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[1] + GECM$coefficients[15]*0 + GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

#Second period after shock
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[3] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[2] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[2]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[1]) + GECM$coefficients[15]*0 + GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

#Third period after shock
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[4] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[3] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[3]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[2]) + GECM$coefficients[15]*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[1] + GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

#Fourth period after shock
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[5] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[4] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[4]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[3]) + GECM$coefficients[15]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[2]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[1]) + GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

#Fifth period after shock
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[6] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[5] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[5]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[4]) + GECM$coefficients[15]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[3]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[2])+ GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

#Sixth period after shock
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[7] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[6] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[6]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[5]) + GECM$coefficients[15]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[4]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[3]) + GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

#Seventh period after shock
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[8] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[7] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[7]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[6]) + GECM$coefficients[15]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[5]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[4]) + GECM$coefficients[16]*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[1]

#Periods 8+ after shock
for (t in 9:21) {
PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t] <-(1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-1] + GECM$coefficients[3]*1 + GECM$coefficients[10]*0 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 +
GECM$coefficients[14]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-1]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-2]) + GECM$coefficients[15]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-4]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-5]) + GECM$coefficients[16]*(PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-7]-PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-8])

  }


#### Plot
ggplot(data = PolAvg.cirf, aes(x = period, y = PolAvgcIRF)) +
               geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
               geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 0),
                          colour = "#990000",
                          linetype = "dashed") +
               ylab("CIRF") +
               xlab("Period") +
               ggtitle("CIRF (PolAvg)") +
               theme_bw()

Here we see that when policy became one point more expansive/generous, preferences for more expansive/liberal policy declined over time, eventually reaching the LRM of 0.393 points more conservative.

The effect in changes in Mood is the same as the period-to-period effects. In the code below, I calculate the immediate effect as the zero period effect. All remaining periods take the current effect from the previous IRFs and subtract the previous period. That is I difference the cumulative effect on levels from above and get changes.

PolAvg.irf <- data.frame(period = c(0:20),
                           PolAvgIRF = NA_real_)

#Zero period
PolAvg.irf$PolAvgIRF[1] <- (1 + GECM$coefficients[2])*0 + GECM$coefficients[3]*0 + GECM$coefficients[10]*1 +  GECM$coefficients[11]*0 + GECM$coefficients[14]*0 + GECM$coefficients[15]*0 + GECM$coefficients[16]*0 

currentvalue <- PolAvg.irf$PolAvgIRF[1]
#Rest of periods
for (t in 2:21) {
    PolAvg.irf$PolAvgIRF[t] <- PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t] - PolAvg.cirf$PolAvgcIRF[t-1]
    currentvalue <- PolAvg.irf$PolAvgIRF[t]
}
ggplot(data = PolAvg.irf, aes(x = period,y = PolAvgIRF)) +
                geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
                ylab("IRF") +
                xlab("Period") +
                ggtitle("Simple Impulse Response Function PolAvg") +
                theme_bw()

Here we see the biggest effects on Mood were in the first and second period, and then generally decay, although the lagged differences of Mood in the model interrupt the general pattern.
